04828nam a22007455i 9780804798013DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015033514  a97808047980137 a10.1515/97808047980132doi  a(DE-B1597)563784  a(OCoLC)1198929684  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aKF4772b.B38 2016 7aLAW1090002bisacsh04a342.7308/531 aBatchis, Wayne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Right's First Amendment :bThe Politics of Free Speech & the Return of Conservative Libertarianism /cWayne Batchis. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Law and Politics00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Right's First Amendment -- t1. Conservatism, the First Amendment, and National Review -- t2. The Political Science of Judicial Decision Making -- t3. Political Correctness and the Rise of the Conservative Victim -- t4. The Courts and the Political Correctness Indictment -- t5. The Rise of Free-Market Conservatism -- t6. Commercial Speech in the Modern Era -- t7. Citizens United and the Paradox of Associational Speech -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNot so long ago, being aggressively "pro-free speech" was as closely associated with American political liberalism as being pro-choice, pro-affirmative action, or pro-gun control. With little notice, this political dynamic has been shaken to the core. The Right's First Amendment examines how conservatives came to adopt and co-opt constitutional free speech rights. In the 1960s, free speech on college campuses was seen as a guarantee for social agitators, hippies, and peaceniks. Today, for many conservatives, it represents instead a crucial shield that protects traditionalists from a perceived scourge of political correctness and liberal oversensitivity. Over a similar period, free market conservatives have risen up to embrace a once unknown, but now cherished, liberty: freedom of commercial expression. What do these changes mean for the future of First Amendment interpretation? Wayne Batchis offers a fresh entry point into these issues by grounding his study in both political and legal scholarship. Surveying six decades of writings from the preeminent conservative publication National Review alongside the evolving constitutional law and ideological predispositions of Supreme Court justices deciding these issues, Batchis asks the conservative political movement to answer to its judicial logic, revealing how this keystone of our civic American beliefs now carries a much more complex and nuanced political identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aConservatismxUnited States. 0aConservatismzUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawxUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aFreedom of speechxUnited States. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited States. 0aJudicial processxUnited States. 0aJudicial processzUnited States. 0aLibertarianismxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aLibertarianismzUnited States. 0aPolitical correctnessxUnited States. 0aPolitical correctnesszUnited States. 4aFirst Amendment. 4aNational Review. 4aSupreme Court. 4acommercial speech. 4aconservative. 4afree speech. 4aideology. 4apolitical correctness. 7aLAW / Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479801340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/